Ignore my comment. Java code would be passing the directory path.
With new MpackAdvisor Java code it would be : 

**MpackAdvisorCommand.java**  -. having mpackRequestDirectory=/run/ambari-server/mpack-recommendations
```
public synchronized T invoke(MpackAdvisorRequest request, ServiceInfo.ServiceAdvisorType serviceAdvisorType) throws MpackAdvisorException {
    ....
    ....
    maRunner.runScript(serviceAdvisorType, getCommandType(), mpackRequestDirectory);
```

Yes you make a lot sense. Generally when I build clusters I do a uniform truststore for the entire cluster. Not everyone does that. 

So in response, for Ranger I am using Ranger's own truststore and password. For Atlas I am using the policy manager plugin's truststore and password because if the cert is not there the audit pieces will not populated as well.
